# Go Performance Rules (Hot Paths)

The proxy must achieve <20ms p99 overhead. Every allocation in the request path is a potential GC pause. Write code that is correct first, then profile before optimising — but never write obviously slow code.

## Pre-allocate slices and maps when size is known

```go
// WRONG — reallocates repeatedly as slice grows
var ids []uuid.UUID
for _, row := range rows {
    ids = append(ids, row.ID)
}

// RIGHT — single allocation
ids := make([]uuid.UUID, 0, len(rows))
for _, row := range rows {
    ids = append(ids, row.ID)
}
```

## strings.Builder for string concatenation

```go
// WRONG — O(n²) allocations; each + allocates a new string
var s string
for _, part := range parts {
    s += part
}

// RIGHT — single underlying buffer
var b strings.Builder
b.Grow(estimatedLen) // pre-grow if length is known
for _, part := range parts {
    b.WriteString(part)
}
return b.String()
```

## Avoid heap allocations in the critical path

```go
// WRONG — error value allocated on heap per request
return fmt.Errorf("rate limit exceeded")

// RIGHT — sentinel error (allocated once at init)
var ErrRateLimited = errors.New("rate limit exceeded")
return ErrRateLimited

// RIGHT — for structured errors that carry per-request data, accept the allocation
// but profile to confirm it's not a bottleneck
return &RateLimitError{Limit: limit, RetryAfter: retryAfter}
```

## sync.Pool for frequently allocated, short-lived objects

```go
// For objects allocated and discarded on every request:
var requestPool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() any { return &RequestContext{} },
}

func handleRequest(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    ctx := requestPool.Get().(*RequestContext)
    defer func() {
        ctx.reset() // clear all fields
        requestPool.Put(ctx)
    }()
    // ...
}
```

## Benchmark before and after any performance optimisation

```go
func BenchmarkRedisSlider_Check(b *testing.B) {
    mr := miniredis.RunT(b)
    slider := NewRedisSlider(redis.NewClient(&redis.Options{Addr: mr.Addr()}), 60)
    ctx := context.Background()

    b.ResetTimer()
    b.ReportAllocs()
    for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ {
        slider.Check(ctx, testOrgID)
    }
}
// Run: go test -bench=BenchmarkRedisSlider_Check -benchmem -count=5
```

## No defer in tight loops

```go
// WRONG — defer in loop; allocates closure per iteration
for _, f := range files {
    f, err := os.Open(f)
    if err != nil { return err }
    defer f.Close() // only called at function return, holds all handles
    process(f)
}

// RIGHT — close explicitly in loop
for _, name := range files {
    if err := processFile(name); err != nil {
        return err
    }
}
func processFile(name string) error {
    f, err := os.Open(name)
    if err != nil { return err }
    defer f.Close() // fine here — one file per function call
    return process(f)
}
```

## Context values are not for performance-critical data

Do not store frequently accessed data (org_id, agent_id) only in context. Context value lookup is a linear search by key. For hot-path data, extract from context once at handler entry and pass explicitly.

```go
// WRONG — repeated context lookups in inner loop
for _, mem := range memories {
    orgID := r.Context().Value(orgIDKey{}).(uuid.UUID) // lookup every iteration
    process(orgID, mem)
}

// RIGHT — extract once
orgID, _ := middleware.OrgIDFromContext(r.Context())
for _, mem := range memories {
    process(orgID, mem)
}
```
